{{for|the Australian politician|Albert Willis (Australian politician)}} {{Infobox ambassador |honorific-prefix = |name = Albert S. Willis |honorific-suffix = |image = Albert S. Willis - Brady Handy cropped2.jpg |imagesize = |alt = A man with receding black hair and a black beard and mustache wearing a black jacket, pulled tightly |order = |ambassador_from1 = United States |country1 = Hawaii |term_start1 = 1893 |term_end1 = January 6, 1897 |predecessor1= [[James Henderson Blount]] |successor1 = [[Harold M. Sewall]] |president1 = [[Grover Cleveland]] |state2 = [[Kentucky]] |district2 = [[Kentucky's 5th congressional district|5th]] |term_start2 = March 4, 1877 |term_end2 = March 3, 1887 |predecessor2= [[Henry Watterson]] |successor2 = [[Asher G. Caruth]] |birth_date = {{birth date|1843|01|22}} |birth_place = [[Shelbyville, Kentucky]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1897|01|06|1843|01|22}} |death_place = [[Honolulu, Hawaii]] |restingplace = [[Cave Hill Cemetery]] |restingplacecoordinates = |birthname = |nationality = |party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] |otherparty = <!--For additional political affiliations--> |spouse = |relations = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = [[University of Louisville School of Law]] |profession = [[Lawyer]] |religion = |signature = |signature_alt = |footnotes = }}
'''Albert Shelby Willis''' (January 22, 1843 &ndash; January 6, 1897) was a [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from [[Kentucky]] and a [[United States Minister to Hawaii|Minister to Hawaii]].
==Life== Born in [[Shelbyville, Kentucky]], Willis attended the [[common school]]s, and graduated from the [[Louisville Male High School]] in 1860. He taught school for four years before graduating from the [[University of Louisville School of Law]] in 1866. He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] and commenced the practice of law in Louisville. He served as [[prosecuting attorney]] for [[Jefferson County, Kentucky|Jefferson County]] from 1874 to 1877.
Willis was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[45th United States Congress|Forty-fifth]] and to the four succeeding Congresses (March 4, 1877 – March 3, 1887). He served as chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Rivers and Harbors|Committee on Rivers and Harbors]] during the [[48th United States Congress|Forty-eighth]] and [[49th United States Congress|Forty-ninth]] Congresses. He was an unsuccessful candidate for renomination in 1886.
[[File:Willis Cartoon.jpg|left|thumb|An 1893 editorial cartoon with Willis, Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani, and President Sanford B. Dole by the newspaper ''The Morning Call'']]He resumed the practice of law before being appointed Minister to [[Hawaii]] by President [[Grover Cleveland]] in 1893. Willis was sent to Hawaii on a secret mission to meet with deposed [[Liliuokalani|Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani]] and obtain a promise of amnesty for those involved in the [[overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii]] if Cleveland restored her to the throne. Willis reported to the Secretary of State in Washington that she was intent on killing the culprits. There was a dispute: Willis said the Queen said "beheading"; she later said she used "execute." <ref>{{cite book|author=Charles W. Calhoun|authorlink=Charles W. Calhoun|title=Gilded Age Cato: The Life of Walter Q. Gresham|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=otUeBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA150|year=2015|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|page=150}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Eric T. L. Love|title=Race over Empire: Racism and U.S. Imperialism, 1865-1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KE_qCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA112|year=2005|publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press|page=112}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nick Cleaver|title=Grover Cleveland's New Foreign Policy: Arbitration, Neutrality, and the Dawn of American Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CtQaBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29|year=2014|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|page=29}}</ref>
Finally the Queen reversed herself and told Willis she could issue an amnesty. On December 18, 1893, Willis demanded on behalf of Cleveland to dissolve the [[Provisional Government of Hawaii]] and restore the Queen to power. Willis' mission was a failure when [[Sanford B. Dole]] sent a written reply declining the surrender of his authority to the deposed queen. President Cleveland then referred the matter to Congress, which commissioned the [[Morgan Report]], which exonerated the U.S. minister and peacekeepers from taking any part in the Hawaiian Revolution. Following the Morgan Report, Cleveland reversed his stance, rebuffed the queen's further pleas for interference, and maintained normal diplomatic relations with both the Provisional Government and its successor the [[Republic of Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Nick Cleaver|title=Grover Cleveland's New Foreign Policy: Arbitration, Neutrality, and the Dawn of American Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CtQaBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|year=2014|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|pages=46–47}}</ref>
Willis served as Minister to Hawaii until his death in [[Honolulu]] on January 6, 1897. An elaborate state funeral was held for him in the [[ʻIolani Palace]] (temporarily renamed the Executive Building).<ref>{{cite news |title= Last Sad Rites: Funeral of U. S. Minister Willis Yesterday: Civis and Military Display: Remains in State at Executive Building |date= January 12, 1897 |newspaper= The Hawaiian gazette |location= Honolulu |url= http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1897-01-12/ed-1/seq-1/ |accessdate= August 8, 2010 }}</ref> He was interred in [[Cave Hill Cemetery]], [[Louisville, Kentucky]].
